&quot;Organisation tries to raise funds for an atomic bomb powered starship!&quot;<br>
The ship itself is perfectly legal. I believe the construction is entirely an engineering challenge. We know enough about the nature of atomic detonations to design a pusher plate, shock absorber system and main structure which will work. What tests are necessary can be simulated on a computer.<br>
That would be the first stage. Then we can put the schematics out over the net. Drive section, cargo bays, habitation area, outer shuttle docking areas, etc. The habitation area might include dining area and even a small pool. People would be mesmerised. Everytime they looked at that abomination the ISS on TV they would cringe with embarassment. Public attitudes might change. Guided tours would be informative of both the pro's and con's of launching a single Orion.<br>
I believe once some money does accumulate more will follow. No upper or lower limit should be set but contributors should get something in return. A small part of the ship is the best answer. When the ship is actually completed they will own a part of it relative to the amount of money contributed. Only a rough estimate of the target figure can be given to start with.<br>
<br>
I'll check into it when I get to Los Angeles. Might contact the Skyrider team for advice. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
